WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.470
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
We are looking at the difficulties&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.470 --> 00:00:21.420
with establishing real numbers as infinite&nbsp;
decimals. These are very serious difficulties,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.420 --> 00:00:28.140
which the professor these days is doing&nbsp;
their best to avoid acknowledging,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:34.680
and there's a good reason for it because&nbsp;
the price to be paid, as we'll see,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:41.250
is quite significant, or at least it appears&nbsp;
to be. However, we'll see that there are great&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:41.250 --> 00:00:45.990
opportunities as well by acknowledging&nbsp;
the difficulties and moving beyond them.

00:00:45.990 --> 00:00:54.510
Last time, we talked about infinite decimals in&nbsp;
terms of infinite choice sequences—the idea that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.510 --> 00:01:02.490
it was possible to prescribe decimals one&nbsp;
at a time, arbitrarily and independently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:10.680
forever and ever. We basically explained very&nbsp;
clearly, I hope, the difficulties with that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:18.840
position. Today, we're going to look at another&nbsp;
approach to infinite decimals: the algorithmic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.840 --> 00:01:28.080
constructive, or computational approach. In this&nbsp;
approach, we think of an infinite decimal as being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:36.510
expressed by an algorithm, so the sequence&nbsp;
of digits that we're trying to get at can be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:36.510 --> 00:01:44.580
captured by an algorithm, a procedure, a function,&nbsp;
a computer program, or some equivalent method.

00:01:44.580 --> 00:01:51.570
So we really have these three positions: the&nbsp;
infinite choice position, the algorithmic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.570 --> 00:01:57.420
constructive, or computational position,&nbsp;
and then a third position, which is really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:04.440
the only one left to us once we acknowledge&nbsp;
the difficulty or impossibility of the first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:09.240
two positions. That third position&nbsp;
is a finitist or rational position,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:16.180
which is that infinite decimals are&nbsp;
illogical and unnecessary. Ultimately,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:16.180 --> 00:02:21.280
this is the position that we are going to adopt,&nbsp;
and I am going to try to show you that mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.280 --> 00:02:29.380
is not impoverished by this position but actually&nbsp;
unfolds before us in a brand new and exciting way.

00:02:29.380 --> 00:02:35.650
Alright, today we're going to look at the&nbsp;
algorithmic, constructive, or computational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.650 --> 00:02:43.900
approach to what is an infinite decimal, and we're&nbsp;
going to look at the pros and cons. Let me start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:50.500
by saying that I have a lot of sympathy for this&nbsp;
approach to infinite decimals. I think this is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.500 --> 00:02:59.590
very reasonable thing to try to do—to try to look&nbsp;
at an infinite decimal like 3.1415926, and so on,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:05.680
with digits that go on and on forever, by&nbsp;
approaching that from the point of view that says,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:13.690
"Well, we need an algorithm that describes the&nbsp;
digits, and we'll think of the infinite decimal as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:20.500
really being encoded by the algorithm." The beauty&nbsp;
of that is that the algorithm is a finite object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:26.440
and so we can work with the infinite decimal&nbsp;
as represented by this finite object. I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:35.470
think that's a very sensible, reasonable, and&nbsp;
natural thing to try to do. The only problem&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.470 --> 00:03:42.910
with it is that it's too difficult to do, and&nbsp;
ultimately, we can't do it in the year 2012.

00:03:42.910 --> 00:03:48.250
Alright, so what do we mean, first&nbsp;
of all, by an algorithm? Clearly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.250 --> 00:03:55.420
we need to think about what that word means.&nbsp;
So intuitively, we might say that it's a finite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.420 --> 00:04:06.160
list of well-defined instructions that give us a&nbsp;
step-by-step procedure for a calculation. Often,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:13.990
the calculation that we want to do is of a&nbsp;
function. This is an English-language definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:19.570
something that you might find in a dictionary.&nbsp;
I don't think at all that it's clear enough and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.570 --> 00:04:24.430
precise enough for mathematical usage, but&nbsp;
at least it gives us an initial orientation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:30.550
to what an algorithm is. Those of you&nbsp;
who are familiar with computers can,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.550 --> 00:04:34.390
if you like, think of it as being&nbsp;
essentially a computer program.

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:45.010
So what we have here, for example, is a piece&nbsp;
of paper or a file on your hard drive with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.010 --> 00:04:50.770
instructions: instruction number one, instruction&nbsp;
number two, perhaps down to instruction number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.770 --> 00:05:00.040
15. These instructions allow us, for example, to&nbsp;
calculate a function to capture this number pi.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:09.280
The function naturally might input the place&nbsp;
of the decimal and output the decimal value,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:09.280 --> 00:05:18.370
so F of 1 equals 1, F of 2 equals 4, F of&nbsp;
3 equals 1, and F of 0 equals 3, let's say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.370 --> 00:05:26.620
F of 7 equals 6, and so on. So the idea&nbsp;
is, you want to know what is the 1, 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:26.620 --> 00:05:36.310
3, 4, 5—the 5th decimal place. So you input the&nbsp;
number 5, perform the operations on the number 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.310 --> 00:05:42.610
eventually you get an output, and hopefully,&nbsp;
that output is the digit 9. And that's how we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:51.250
can specify the entire infinite decimal by a&nbsp;
very finite, cut-and-dried procedure. It's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.250 --> 00:05:57.580
very attractive idea, an attractive&nbsp;
idea which ultimately doesn't work.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:07.180
As we go down this route, it's clear that there&nbsp;
are some significant challenges ahead of us. First&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:15.490
of all, we are going to need an underlying&nbsp;
theory or understanding of algorithms. We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.490 --> 00:06:22.960
going to have to know a lot about algorithms: what&nbsp;
they are, how they work, how they're implemented.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:22.960 --> 00:06:30.040
We need a theory of algorithms. Secondly, we're&nbsp;
going to have to acknowledge that conceptually,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:35.980
this framework for establishing a number&nbsp;
system is much, much more complicated than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:35.980 --> 00:06:45.510
for rational numbers. Rational numbers—1/6 plus&nbsp;
2/7 equals 19 over 42—what a rational number is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:53.970
is pretty simple. It's a pair of integers;&nbsp;
how we add them is reasonably simple;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.970 --> 00:07:00.870
how we multiply them is reasonably simple. Here,&nbsp;
what we're going to be dealing with is algorithms,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:06.330
computer programs, and we're going to have to&nbsp;
deal with the challenge of how you add them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:14.400
how you multiply them, how you check the&nbsp;
laws of arithmetic. It's a big challenge.

00:07:14.400 --> 00:07:22.230
We'll probably need help from computer science&nbsp;
because we're talking about algorithms. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:26.940
computer scientists know all about algorithms.&nbsp;
They're the ones who work with these things;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:33.450
they have very elaborate experience and&nbsp;
theories for them. However, within mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.450 --> 00:07:41.400
there's also the theory of computation.&nbsp;
Mathematicians also study computation. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:41.400 --> 00:07:46.050
there's something called the lambda calculus,&nbsp;
there are things called Turing machines,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:46.050 --> 00:07:51.780
there's something called automata theory, and&nbsp;
other things as well. And the question is, will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:51.780 --> 00:08:00.420
we need any of these theories in order to set up&nbsp;
our approach to infinite decimals as algorithms?

00:08:00.420 --> 00:08:08.940
Alright, so what are the pros and cons of&nbsp;
trying to look at infinite decimals in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:15.780
algorithms? Well, there are lots of advantages;&nbsp;
there are lots of good reasons for trying to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:15.780 --> 00:08:23.400
do this. The first one, perhaps, is that this&nbsp;
general orientation agrees with the historical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:31.350
point of view. Historically, the infinite decimals&nbsp;
that people dealt with were given by procedures,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:42.570
by algorithms, by rules that generated digits one&nbsp;
at a time. For example, the square root algorithm,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:50.280
which we've talked about several points in this&nbsp;
series, going back to the Babylonians. The Hindus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.280 --> 00:08:58.290
had such an algorithm, the Greeks, the Arabs,&nbsp;
and then Newton for square root of 2, square root&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:58.290 --> 00:09:06.090
of 5, and so on. These are procedures that work&nbsp;
step by step, and they allow us to get closer and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.090 --> 00:09:11.880
closer to rational approximations, which can be&nbsp;
converted into further and further initial strings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:11.880 --> 00:09:20.010
of a decimal. There's also a cube root algorithm,&nbsp;
which we haven't talked about, but it's a more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:20.010 --> 00:09:25.650
sophisticated version of a square root algorithm.&nbsp;
In fact, it was studied by ancient Indian&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:25.650 --> 00:09:31.710
mathematician Aryabhata around 500 AD, and of&nbsp;
course, it's also accessible by Newton's method.

00:09:31.710 --> 00:09:40.470
And then we must mention pi, which plays&nbsp;
a very big role in the history of people's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:48.600
fascination with infinite decimals. So pi has&nbsp;
been tackled going back to Archimedes, who&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.600 --> 00:09:58.710
initiated an essentially algorithmic process for&nbsp;
approximating pi. But the first, perhaps modern,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.710 --> 00:10:05.550
formula goes back to an Indian mathematician&nbsp;
Madhava from Kerala in southern India in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:05.550 --> 00:10:12.540
1300s, who came up with this remarkable formula&nbsp;
that pi is equal to the square root of 12 times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:21.870
[1 minus 1 over 3 times 3 plus 1 over 5 times 3&nbsp;
squared minus 1 over 7 times 3 cubed, and so on].&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:30.060
So each one of these terms is getting smaller&nbsp;
because the denominators are getting bigger,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:38.910
keep multiplying by the next odd number and&nbsp;
then by powers of 3. So we're adding and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.910 --> 00:10:43.980
subtracting smaller and smaller quantities,&nbsp;
and if you go to a certain number of terms,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:43.980 --> 00:10:50.370
then you can compute a relatively accurate&nbsp;
approximation to pi provided you also know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:50.370 --> 00:10:56.490
how to take a square root of 2. And Madhava, in&nbsp;
fact, was able to calculate pi to this number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:56.490 --> 00:11:07.030
decimal places using 21 terms of this series. Now,&nbsp;
this is an algorithmic approach. You have a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.030 --> 00:11:12.010
cut-and-dried formula. You can go as far as you&nbsp;
want in this formula. You can compute something;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.010 --> 00:11:19.510
you get an initial part of the decimal. So&nbsp;
in principle, you can keep going, keep going,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:19.510 --> 00:11:27.010
getting more and more digits this way. So&nbsp;
the decimal is encoded by this formula,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:27.010 --> 00:11:32.380
which we could think of these days as also&nbsp;
a procedure or computer program if we like.

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:40.120
And historically, there have been many, many&nbsp;
other formulas for pi. In my next video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:40.120 --> 00:11:45.100
in fact, we are going to have a good look at pi&nbsp;
and some of the many formulas that people have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:45.100 --> 00:11:52.000
come up with that essentially give us algorithms&nbsp;
for computing pi. Alright, so historically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:58.390
this point of view corresponds to&nbsp;
what people used to think. Stevin,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:58.390 --> 00:12:04.960
when he introduced real numbers in the 17th&nbsp;
century, would have been thinking about these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:10.660
infinite decimals in this algorithmic fashion&nbsp;
because the main examples that he would have had,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:18.430
like roots and pi, were of that form.&nbsp;
Also, I suppose repeating decimals,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.430 --> 00:12:25.360
which are also a special and very simple&nbsp;
example of an algorithm that generates digits.

00:12:25.360 --> 00:12:31.570
Another advantage to this algorithmic&nbsp;
approach, if we can make it work,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:31.570 --> 00:12:39.280
is that it allows evaluation of so-called&nbsp;
infinite series. These are very important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:45.280
constructions in analysis, and the real&nbsp;
numbers, as we currently have them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:53.200
allow us—or seem to allow us—to evaluate&nbsp;
these things. For example, consider this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:53.200 --> 00:12:59.620
infinite series. So it's an infinite series in&nbsp;
the sense that we're adding more and more terms,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:59.620 --> 00:13:04.870
but the terms that we're adding are getting&nbsp;
smaller and smaller, so we're converging&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:10.930
to something, we think, and that something&nbsp;
that we're converging to is a real number.

00:13:10.930 --> 00:13:17.400
Now, this series here, the terms are&nbsp;
actually forming a very nice and important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:23.370
pattern. Here we have 1 over 2, and then 1&nbsp;
over 2 times 3, and then 2 times 3 times 4,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:30.960
2 times 3 times 4 times 5, and the denominators—so&nbsp;
these numbers are called factorials. So we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:37.320
write this summation more compactly using&nbsp;
this summation sign introduced by Euler.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:46.320
So we're summing from N equals 0 to infinity&nbsp;
1 over N factorial. 1 over 0 factorial is 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:52.260
by definition because 0 factorial is&nbsp;
defined to be 1. Then there's 1 over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.260 --> 00:13:57.750
1 factorial, 1 over 2 factorial, 1 over 3&nbsp;
factorial, 1 over 4 factorial, and so on.

00:13:57.750 --> 00:14:07.410
So how do we approach such an infinite series?&nbsp;
Through the idea of partial sums, where we go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:16.530
from N equals 0 to some fixed natural number K.&nbsp;
So in other words, we add up all the terms up to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:16.530 --> 00:14:23.610
a certain amount and compute what we've got. So&nbsp;
in this case, the first partial sum is just that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.610 --> 00:14:29.550
first term, which is 1. The second partial sum,&nbsp;
the first two terms, that's 2. Then the next one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:29.550 --> 00:14:37.830
will be 5/2. As a decimal, 2.5. And then when&nbsp;
we add this term here, we get 8/3, which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:45.960
2.6 repeated. Then we add this one on top of it,&nbsp;
and we get 65/24, which turns out to be 2.7083&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.250 --> 00:15:05.940
repeated. Then s5 is 163/60—that's 2.716 repeated.&nbsp;
s6 is this, s7 is this, and s8 is this, starting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.940 --> 00:15:10.890
to get a little bit more complicated here. The&nbsp;
repetition only kicks in at this level here.

00:15:10.890 --> 00:15:20.430
Now, if we look at all these partial sums, we see&nbsp;
that they are sort of converging to something in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:20.430 --> 00:15:28.110
the sense that the first terms start to stabilize&nbsp;
after a while. So here we get 2.718, and here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.110 --> 00:15:36.330
another 2.718, 2.718. All the further terms are&nbsp;
going to have 2.718 in them. So as we keep going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:36.330 --> 00:15:46.740
and keep going, we end up generating more and&nbsp;
more digits. So this is really an algorithm;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:46.740 --> 00:15:56.640
it's really a step-by-step procedure that can be&nbsp;
used to create an infinite decimal step by step,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:56.640 --> 00:16:06.030
slowly, slowly, more and more. Here is&nbsp;
the limiting value. The limiting value is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:06.030 --> 00:16:11.250
a very important number called e—that's the&nbsp;
base of natural logarithms. It plays a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.250 --> 00:16:24.660
important role in mathematics. It's 2.71828,&nbsp;
1828459045235360287, and so on and so on. Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.660 --> 00:16:31.110
it's represented by exactly this infinite&nbsp;
series, and we can think of this infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:38.040
series in terms of an algorithm. It's laying&nbsp;
out a procedure for calculating more and more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:38.040 --> 00:16:46.170
of these infinite decimals. So the advantage is&nbsp;
we don't need to think about the object itself as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:46.170 --> 00:16:50.640
being this infinite decimal going on forever&nbsp;
and ever and ever and ever. We don't have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:56.190
become philosophical about what does "forever and&nbsp;
ever and ever" mean because we can just work with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.190 --> 00:17:06.390
this formula. This formula is essentially encoding&nbsp;
this decimal. The formula is a very finite thing;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:15.270
it presents us with a very simple algorithm&nbsp;
that generates the decimal. So it's the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.270 --> 00:17:20.730
kind of idea as when we use something like&nbsp;
this with a repeating decimal. We had some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:27.240
finite expression that actually encodes something&nbsp;
that we can think of as going on forever, but the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:27.240 --> 00:17:34.260
actual expression that we're using is finite. The&nbsp;
expression is finite; it's a finite algorithm.

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:43.590
So this is one big advantage: that the infinite&nbsp;
series can be summed this way. Of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:43.590 --> 00:17:48.090
there's a little bit of a catch. The series has&nbsp;
to have the property that the terms that we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:48.090 --> 00:17:54.930
adding get small sufficiently fast so that there's&nbsp;
some kind of convergence so that we do actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.930 --> 00:18:00.630
end up stabilizing and that these things don't&nbsp;
start wandering around as we add more terms. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.630 --> 00:18:09.720
not all infinite series are summable in this way,&nbsp;
but the convergent ones are, and we do need this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.720 --> 00:18:17.670
theory of real numbers, it seems, to sum them. And&nbsp;
this is one big advantage in thinking about real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:17.670 --> 00:18:23.340
numbers this way—in this algorithmic way—that&nbsp;
it allows us to sum convergent infinite series.

00:18:23.340 --> 00:18:33.990
Another big advantage of the algorithmic approach&nbsp;
is that it allows us to define many functions. For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.990 --> 00:18:41.670
example, the exponential function, a key function&nbsp;
in modern analysis, which we can define this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.670 --> 00:18:50.490
way along with Euler: the limit as n approaches&nbsp;
infinity of (1 + x/n) to the nth power. So we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:59.250
inputting x, and we're outputting this thing.&nbsp;
Well, this thing is really an algorithm, or it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:59.250 --> 00:19:07.470
a procedure that allows us to calculate more and&nbsp;
more digits of some decimal number. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:07.470 --> 00:19:16.350
suppose we want to calculate e squared, or the&nbsp;
x of 2. So the x has the value 2; we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.350 --> 00:19:22.710
to replace this with 2. So what we have to do is&nbsp;
we have to calculate this expression for a given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.710 --> 00:19:28.920
value of n, n equals 1, and then n equals 2, and&nbsp;
then n equals 3, and so on, and keep going, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.920 --> 00:19:36.780
hopefully, the digits that we get will stabilize&nbsp;
and give us ultimately a decimal expression.

00:19:36.780 --> 00:19:44.580
So what happens in this case? Well, in the&nbsp;
case n equals 1, we have 1 plus 2 over 1 to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:44.580 --> 00:19:52.020
the 1st power, which equals 3. When n is 2, we get&nbsp;
1 plus 2 over 2 squared, which is 4. When n is 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.020 --> 00:20:02.930
1 plus 2 over 3 cubed, which is this 4.629&nbsp;
repeated. When n is 4, we get 5.0625—it's a finite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:14.690
decimal or a decimal number. When n is 5, we&nbsp;
get 5.3782 for another decimal number. And here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.690 --> 00:20:20.960
1 plus 2 over 6 to the 6th power—well, it's&nbsp;
some repeating decimal because it's a fraction,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.960 --> 00:20:28.490
but actually, the repeating part&nbsp;
is too long to easily contain here.

00:20:28.490 --> 00:20:36.290
So what's happening to these numbers? Are&nbsp;
they progressing towards some goal? Are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:36.290 --> 00:20:41.810
they stabilizing? Well, in fact, they are not&nbsp;
stabilizing very clearly at this level here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:41.810 --> 00:20:47.330
and that's because we haven't chosen enough&nbsp;
n's. We haven't gone far enough to even start&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:54.560
seeing a pattern. It turns out that the&nbsp;
limit of these things is this real number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:54.560 --> 00:21:03.290
7.389056098, and so on. And to get&nbsp;
the first three digits here, the 7.38,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:13.550
so in order to get 7.38 consistently, you&nbsp;
need to go to n being around 1600. You&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:13.550 --> 00:21:18.710
need to go a long way in this series before&nbsp;
you even start getting the first few terms.

00:21:18.710 --> 00:21:27.560
Alright, well, this can happen. There's no&nbsp;
indication about how long we have to go before&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.560 --> 00:21:35.660
we get to what we want, but nevertheless, this&nbsp;
thing does converge. And as we go further and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:35.660 --> 00:21:41.240
further with increasing values of n, then we&nbsp;
end up generating more and more and more of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:47.600
these digits, and this is e squared, which is&nbsp;
exactly the square of that number e that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:47.600 --> 00:21:57.930
had on our previous slide. So this approach to&nbsp;
real numbers as algorithms allows us to define&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:57.930 --> 00:22:06.300
many important functions of modern analysis,&nbsp;
so it's a very key application of the idea.

00:22:06.300 --> 00:22:13.110
A fourth major advantage in this algorithmic&nbsp;
approach is that it allows us to define and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:13.110 --> 00:22:20.250
evaluate integrals. Integrals are a key tool&nbsp;
for modern analysis and modern mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:29.070
more generally. So, for example, and I'm just&nbsp;
giving an overview here, this is not a careful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:29.070 --> 00:22:36.120
exposition of either integrals or analytic&nbsp;
functions or infinite series. I'm just giving&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:36.120 --> 00:22:42.360
you a taste of some of these ideas. So here's&nbsp;
the function f of x equals e to the negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:48.270
x squared. So it's that exponential function&nbsp;
we were considering before with now a minus x&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:48.270 --> 00:22:55.620
squared input into it. If we graph it, we get&nbsp;
something that looks like this. It's a famous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:55.620 --> 00:23:03.240
bell curve shape. And let's say that we're&nbsp;
interested in the integral from 0 to 1 of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:12.210
function. And that means we're trying to estimate&nbsp;
or find the area under this graph from 0 to 1.

00:23:12.210 --> 00:23:19.770
Okay, so there are various ways of trying to&nbsp;
define what this integral is. And one way, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:19.770 --> 00:23:26.190
was introduced by the famous German mathematician&nbsp;
Riemann in the middle of the 19th century,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:35.700
is in terms of a limit of approximating sums of&nbsp;
rectangles. So what we can think of here is, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:41.910
we can divide the interval from 0 to 1 into n&nbsp;
equal little pieces. And for each one of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:41.910 --> 00:23:47.730
little pieces, we're going to build a rectangle&nbsp;
whose height is the function's value at, say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:47.730 --> 00:23:53.610
the rightmost endpoint of the interval. So in&nbsp;
this case, we get all these little rectangles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:53.610 --> 00:24:01.740
which are just lying underneath the curve, and we&nbsp;
can calculate the sum of all these little areas,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:01.740 --> 00:24:06.820
and that's what this is. So here is&nbsp;
the common width of the rectangle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:14.650
and here are the various heights of the&nbsp;
rectangles, summed from 1 to n, the values&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:14.650 --> 00:24:19.780
of the function. These are the values at these&nbsp;
various points of this particular function.

00:24:19.780 --> 00:24:28.300
Alright, this kind of expression cannot be&nbsp;
calculated within the framework of rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:33.490
numbers, except in an approximate way. But&nbsp;
the real numbers ostensibly give us a way&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:33.490 --> 00:24:39.220
to actually complete the calculation—to get&nbsp;
something that's not approximate but actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:39.220 --> 00:24:46.570
something that's exactly correct. Okay, so what&nbsp;
ends up happening is that we have to calculate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:46.570 --> 00:24:53.890
this sum for various values of n. So, for&nbsp;
example, when n is 2, then we have 1/2 of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:53.890 --> 00:25:00.220
e to the negative 1/4 plus e to the negative&nbsp;
1, which turns out to be this. When n is 5,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:00.220 --> 00:25:06.820
meaning we have 5 little rectangles sitting&nbsp;
under the curve from 0 to 1, then the sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:06.820 --> 00:25:14.320
of the rectangles is 1/5 e to the negative&nbsp;
1/20 plus e to the negative 4/25 to e to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:21.580
negative 1. These are the various heights of the&nbsp;
rectangles. Work that out, and we get something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:28.900
like this. When n equals 10, 1/10, the same kind&nbsp;
of sum with 10 terms, we get something like this.

00:25:28.900 --> 00:25:34.960
We need to make some remarks about the&nbsp;
calculations here. So the calculation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:34.960 --> 00:25:43.060
here is involving already these terms here, which&nbsp;
themselves are given by algorithms. So we have an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:43.060 --> 00:25:48.490
algorithm for e to the x, so we have an algorithm&nbsp;
for e to the negative 1/4, and that's the kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:48.490 --> 00:25:54.370
thing that we're using. We have two of those; we&nbsp;
have to be able to sum them up and divide by two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:54.370 --> 00:26:03.550
to get this term here. So this is not a case&nbsp;
of having rational numbers that we're using;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:03.550 --> 00:26:09.130
we're already using real numbers at each&nbsp;
stage here. And then the idea is to look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:09.130 --> 00:26:15.640
at these numbers, and as n gets big, to see&nbsp;
if they start trending towards some values,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:22.750
and it turns out that they do. You want to go&nbsp;
further than n equals 10, so as we keep going,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:22.750 --> 00:26:27.880
we slowly start converging to&nbsp;
a decimal that looks like this.

00:26:27.880 --> 00:26:35.590
Okay, so this is just a very quick introduction&nbsp;
to integration, which we haven't talked at all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:35.590 --> 00:26:39.490
about in this course up till now. We&nbsp;
will eventually talk about integrals,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.490 --> 00:26:50.380
but just to give you a sense of the claim&nbsp;
that real numbers as algorithms do allow us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:59.620
to calculate integrals under functions, and this&nbsp;
is a primary advantage and good reason for having&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:59.620 --> 00:27:06.820
real numbers as algorithms around. So this is&nbsp;
something that a mathematician values highly.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:06.820 --> 00:27:13.390
We like to be able to integrate; we like to&nbsp;
be able to get answers to things like this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:13.390 --> 00:27:19.840
and real numbers are seemingly providing that&nbsp;
framework for doing that. Real numbers ultimately,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:25.090
in terms of an algorithm, because contained&nbsp;
in the idea of an integral is really the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:25.090 --> 00:27:31.870
algorithm described by Riemann,&nbsp;
but actually going back to Newton.

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:38.980
So there are quite a few more advantages&nbsp;
to real numbers in terms of algorithms,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:38.980 --> 00:27:44.140
but they sort of follow the same kind of line,&nbsp;
and they're often consequences of the ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:50.170
I've already mentioned. In addition, we have the&nbsp;
advantages that I laid out for infinite decimals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:50.170 --> 00:27:56.140
in terms of infinite choice in my previous&nbsp;
video. We have things like the existence of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:56.140 --> 00:28:03.040
the intermediate value theorem, which is&nbsp;
also really an algorithmic procedure. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:03.040 --> 00:28:08.800
have the existence of the fundamental theorem&nbsp;
of algebra, the factorization of polynomials,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:17.770
which is also an algorithmic procedure. So there's&nbsp;
a whole host of mathematical theorems that rely on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:23.230
real numbers, properties of real numbers, which&nbsp;
are intimately connected with the algorithmic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:23.230 --> 00:28:29.120
aspect in this respect that we're talking&nbsp;
about now. So we have a lot of good reasons&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:29.120 --> 00:28:35.360
for wanting to have real numbers and wanting&nbsp;
to have real numbers in terms of algorithms.

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:46.460
However, the painful reality is that there are&nbsp;
serious problems, so let's have a look at some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:46.460 --> 00:28:59.780
of the difficulties. Alright, the first is that&nbsp;
this theory is very, very difficult to set up. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:59.780 --> 00:29:03.830
what are some of the difficulties? Well, first&nbsp;
of all, we have to decide what exactly is an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:03.830 --> 00:29:09.050
algorithm? What are we going to be talking about?&nbsp;
What is an algorithm? What is a computer program?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:09.050 --> 00:29:15.770
What is a procedure? What kind of functions&nbsp;
are we going to be considering when we talk&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:15.770 --> 00:29:19.610
about algorithms or computer programs? We're&nbsp;
often thinking about having a certain machine,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:19.610 --> 00:29:26.540
we're working in C++ or in Pascal or in&nbsp;
Fortran or something. So what machine,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:26.540 --> 00:29:34.160
what language, what formulas are you going&nbsp;
to allow? There are some subtle issues but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:34.160 --> 00:29:39.560
important issues about whether you're going&nbsp;
to allow bounded or unbounded running times.

00:29:39.560 --> 00:29:45.140
So if you have an algorithm, say,&nbsp;
that generates the nth digit of pi,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:45.140 --> 00:29:51.230
and I'm interested in calculating the billionth&nbsp;
digit of pi using your algorithm, a natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:51.230 --> 00:29:59.300
question is how long is this going to take me?&nbsp;
Okay, so the issue here is, do I know ahead of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:06.560
time roughly how long this is going to take me&nbsp;
to calculate this billionth digit? For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:06.560 --> 00:30:10.970
you might tell me this is going to take&nbsp;
me, you know, 24 hours, or maybe 24 days,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:10.970 --> 00:30:17.510
or maybe 24 years, but if it's going to take me&nbsp;
24 centuries, then I probably want to know that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:23.750
before I start with the algorithm. And if&nbsp;
you don't know how long it's going to take,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:23.750 --> 00:30:29.150
it might be that your algorithm is such that&nbsp;
it's unclear how long it's going to take. It&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:29.150 --> 00:30:36.290
might take 24 billion years—well, then that's&nbsp;
a serious obstacle. So the question is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:36.290 --> 00:30:41.930
are we going to specify that algorithms&nbsp;
are bounded or unbounded in running time?

00:30:41.930 --> 00:30:49.310
A related issue is, do we require certificates&nbsp;
of boundedness? So if you come to me with an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:49.310 --> 00:30:56.660
algorithm, and you claim it's a bounded algorithm,&nbsp;
I might want to know, well, are you going to give&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:56.660 --> 00:31:01.550
me a proof of that fact, or am I just going&nbsp;
to take your word for it? So is the proof of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:01.550 --> 00:31:07.160
the boundedness of an algorithm part of the data&nbsp;
that we're going to demand from our algorithms?

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:13.400
So let's suppose that we've overcome these&nbsp;
difficulties. Let's suppose that we've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:13.400 --> 00:31:18.320
established what framework we're working in.&nbsp;
We know exactly what an algorithm is in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:18.320 --> 00:31:23.060
context. We've decided what kind of machines&nbsp;
we're working on, and so on, and we've answered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:28.130
these questions. Then there are these very,&nbsp;
very significant challenges that loom ahead.

00:31:28.130 --> 00:31:33.410
We're going to have to define, of course,&nbsp;
the operations—the operations of addition&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:33.410 --> 00:31:38.900
and multiplication, and then ultimately of&nbsp;
subtraction and division too—but let's focus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:38.900 --> 00:31:45.920
on these. So if you have one algorithm for a real&nbsp;
number, and I have another algorithm for a real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:52.130
number—so algorithm 1 and algorithm 2—how are we&nbsp;
going to combine those two algorithms to give a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:52.130 --> 00:32:01.190
third algorithm for the sum of our numbers? If my&nbsp;
algorithm generates a decimal number, and yours&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:01.190 --> 00:32:05.930
does too, if we add those decimals, we're going&nbsp;
to get another decimal number, and that's going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:05.930 --> 00:32:11.630
to be also given by an algorithm. The question is,&nbsp;
how do you get algorithm 3 from algorithm 1 and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:20.990
algorithm 2? How do you define this operation at&nbsp;
the level of algorithms? And you're going to have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:20.990 --> 00:32:24.890
to worry that this is well-defined because&nbsp;
there are lots of real numbers that have a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:24.890 --> 00:32:31.190
whole bunch of different algorithms that&nbsp;
define them, so you're going to have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:31.190 --> 00:32:36.140
have a check to make sure that your definition&nbsp;
of addition of algorithms, whatever it may be,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:36.140 --> 00:32:40.700
is actually well-defined. And you're going&nbsp;
to, of course, have to do the same thing with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:40.700 --> 00:32:45.740
multiplication, which is going to be even harder.&nbsp;
And then, once you've done that, you're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:45.740 --> 00:32:50.780
have to prove that the laws of arithmetic&nbsp;
work. You're going to have to prove that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:50.780 --> 00:32:56.570
the distributive law works for your definitions&nbsp;
of addition and multiplication of algorithms.

00:32:56.570 --> 00:33:02.060
Now, let me point out to you a very serious&nbsp;
challenge that you're going to have to deal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:02.060 --> 00:33:08.930
with. So this is the same problem that we saw&nbsp;
with the infinite choice approach to infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:08.930 --> 00:33:16.100
decimals. The problem is, what happens when,&nbsp;
at the decimal digit level, you end up with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:22.430
some nines? So let's say we're adding these two&nbsp;
numbers, and here are the actual decimal numbers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:22.430 --> 00:33:27.050
We don't know what the algorithms are, just at&nbsp;
the decimal number level. So one, eight, eight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:27.050 --> 00:33:33.380
and here is one plus four is five, but the next&nbsp;
sum is nine. So we have to check what's happening&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:37.970
before we can write down a five because there&nbsp;
might be a six here if that nine spills over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:37.970 --> 00:33:42.680
and gives us a carry. And here we have zero plus&nbsp;
nine, that's nine; two plus seven, another nine;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:42.680 --> 00:33:48.380
another nine, another nine, another nine,&nbsp;
another nine, another nine. So the question is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:48.380 --> 00:33:54.500
what is your algorithm going to do at this exact&nbsp;
point right here? Your algorithm for adding these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:54.500 --> 00:34:02.210
decimals has got to come up with that digit. So&nbsp;
your algorithm can detect that there's a nine&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:02.210 --> 00:34:07.670
summed next, and then another nine appearing,&nbsp;
another nine here. And, for example, it can try&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:07.670 --> 00:34:15.050
to check the next thousand or million places,&nbsp;
and if you don't get some nines at some point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:19.700
well then you're alright, but if you get a&nbsp;
total of nine for the next million places,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:19.700 --> 00:34:23.300
at some point your algorithm is going to&nbsp;
have to say, "Alright, wait a minute. We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:23.300 --> 00:34:28.760
going to have to stop checking and see whether&nbsp;
we can otherwise determine what this thing is."

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:36.440
So you have a big advantage working with&nbsp;
algorithms rather than with infinite choice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:36.440 --> 00:34:42.770
because you know what the algorithm&nbsp;
is that generates this digit sequence,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:42.770 --> 00:34:48.500
and you know what algorithm it is that generates&nbsp;
this digit sequence, so in principle, it might be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:48.500 --> 00:34:56.630
possible for you to analyze those algorithms and&nbsp;
see whether this pattern of matching up numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:56.630 --> 00:35:03.770
adding up to nine, continues indefinitely or&nbsp;
not. That's the question: Does the sequence of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:03.770 --> 00:35:08.300
nines we're getting continue indefinitely, or&nbsp;
does it eventually stop and give us something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:13.520
else? Because you have the algorithms, you&nbsp;
are at least theoretically in a position&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:13.520 --> 00:35:21.500
to check that by analyzing the structure of the&nbsp;
algorithms. But that's going to be a horrendously&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:21.500 --> 00:35:26.960
difficult thing to do, okay? And probably, to&nbsp;
be honest, it's probably not even possible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:26.960 --> 00:35:31.250
but let's give you the benefit of the&nbsp;
doubt, alright? It's going to be very,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:31.250 --> 00:35:35.120
very, horrendously difficult, and you have&nbsp;
to be able to deal with this. So you have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:42.050
to build into your algorithms for addition&nbsp;
and multiplication this exact issue here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:42.050 --> 00:35:47.180
of how to deal with nines that appear, that&nbsp;
seem to go on forever, but you're not sure.

00:35:47.180 --> 00:35:56.630
Alright, in the year 2012, I'm confident in saying&nbsp;
that no such theory exists. We're not even close&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:56.630 --> 00:36:05.660
to having a theory of real numbers as infinite&nbsp;
decimals generated by algorithms in this fashion.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:05.660 --> 00:36:16.070
It just does not exist. No one has come up with&nbsp;
such a thing. It's just the reality of it. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:16.070 --> 00:36:20.330
I think this is a great project. It's a&nbsp;
great project in the sense that even if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:20.330 --> 00:36:27.230
we were able to make some small progress, it&nbsp;
would be very interesting. So, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:27.230 --> 00:36:34.010
you might be able to generate a theory like this&nbsp;
that works not with general algorithms but rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:34.010 --> 00:36:40.790
algorithms of a rather specialized kind—something&nbsp;
like repeating decimals, but maybe just a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:40.790 --> 00:36:47.600
bit more complicated than repeating decimals.&nbsp;
Again, I don't know of any theory that goes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:47.600 --> 00:36:55.520
beyond repeating decimals, except when you're&nbsp;
kind of looking at finite field extensions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:55.520 --> 00:37:02.240
which you can encode algorithmically if you want&nbsp;
to, but something that's sort of significantly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:08.150
beyond finite field extensions—I don't know of&nbsp;
such a theory. But it would be very interesting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:12.500
if someone were able to come up with such&nbsp;
a thing. So I don't say it's impossible;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:12.500 --> 00:37:18.300
maybe some clever people in the future will&nbsp;
be able to derive and create such a theory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:18.300 --> 00:37:26.700
but currently, we do not have such a thing. So&nbsp;
my criticism of this theory is, in some sense,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:35.610
I'm criticizing something that doesn't really&nbsp;
exist. This is a dream; it's a dream currently.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:35.610 --> 00:37:40.920
So even though it'd be great to have such&nbsp;
a theory, we do not have such a theory.

00:37:40.920 --> 00:37:51.150
A second key problem is the non-uniqueness&nbsp;
of algorithms. The exponential function,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:51.150 --> 00:37:57.720
for example, that we talked about earlier, I gave&nbsp;
you Euler's definition of it. Here is a quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:57.720 --> 00:38:06.180
different definition of that exponential&nbsp;
function as an infinite series. In fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:06.180 --> 00:38:10.500
you can sort of see when x is equal to 1, we're&nbsp;
getting that value for e that we talked about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:10.500 --> 00:38:15.720
earlier. Alright, so you could encode this&nbsp;
infinite series in terms of an algorithm.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:19.920
Then we have two different algorithms that&nbsp;
look, on the face of it, very different,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:19.920 --> 00:38:27.540
which in fact are generating the same function.&nbsp;
Unfortunately, there is no computable way of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:27.540 --> 00:38:34.410
checking if two algorithms generate the same&nbsp;
infinite decimal. There's no way of taking two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:34.410 --> 00:38:39.900
random algorithms and methodically checking&nbsp;
some condition to say, "Ah, these algorithms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:39.900 --> 00:38:46.860
generate the same infinite decimal." There's no&nbsp;
way of doing that. It's a very serious problem.

00:38:46.860 --> 00:38:56.940
So to give you an illustration of that, here is&nbsp;
a specific example that rests on the classical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:56.940 --> 00:39:05.400
number theoretical problem of whether there are&nbsp;
any odd perfect numbers. So a perfect number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:05.400 --> 00:39:13.260
is a number like 6, whose sum of its divisors,&nbsp;
less than itself, equals the number itself. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:19.590
6 is the sum of its divisors, less than it is&nbsp;
1 plus 2 plus 3. Those are the divisors of 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:19.590 --> 00:39:26.070
and they sum up to 6, so 6 is perfect. 28&nbsp;
is also perfect because its divisors are 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:26.070 --> 00:39:33.780
2, 4, 7, and 14, and they also sum up to&nbsp;
twenty-eight. The question is, are there any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:33.780 --> 00:39:39.270
odd perfect numbers? No one knows the answer&nbsp;
to that famous number theoretical problem.

00:39:39.270 --> 00:39:47.640
So, unfortunately or fortunately, we could&nbsp;
build in such a number theoretical conundrum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:47.640 --> 00:39:56.490
into an algorithm. So here's a little algorithm&nbsp;
to compute the nth digit of this decimal. Let's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:56.490 --> 00:40:04.200
call it x. Here's what you do: First of all,&nbsp;
you find the nth number. Let's call it k. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:04.200 --> 00:40:13.230
for example, if n happens to be 8, the 8th odd&nbsp;
number is 15, okay? Next, you calculate the sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:13.230 --> 00:40:23.100
s of all the divisors d, which are less than k,&nbsp;
okay? So, for example, for 15, the divisors are 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:31.260
3, and 5. We calculate the sum, that's 9, okay?&nbsp;
And we're calling that s, okay? If s equals k,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:31.260 --> 00:40:39.300
then we set the 8th digit to be equal to 1, and&nbsp;
if s is not equal to k, then we set the nth digit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:49.590
to be 0. So here, is s equal to k? Is 9 equal to&nbsp;
15? No, it's not, which is telling us that 15 is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:49.590 --> 00:40:56.910
not an odd perfect number. So the instruction&nbsp;
is to set the 8th digit to be equal to zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:56.910 --> 00:41:08.220
alright? So this is a little algorithm which is&nbsp;
exactly going to output 0 here unless the nth odd&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:08.220 --> 00:41:18.000
number is perfect, in which case we'll get a 1. So&nbsp;
we know that the first, you know, billion trillion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:24.240
numbers, whatever, there are no odd numbers that&nbsp;
are perfect in there, so we can be sure that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:24.240 --> 00:41:32.010
number that we're generating with this algorithm&nbsp;
starts 0.00000000 and goes on with zeros for at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:32.010 --> 00:41:41.010
least a few billion, but we don't know whether&nbsp;
this number is actually 0 or not. It's given by an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:41.010 --> 00:41:47.490
algorithm. The algorithm is completely precise; we&nbsp;
can code our computer, we can turn it on, but we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:47.490 --> 00:41:53.850
don't know whether that number is zero or not. It&nbsp;
might be that somewhere way down there, trillions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:53.850 --> 00:42:02.430
and trillions and trillions and trillions further&nbsp;
along, a one appears, okay? So we have no way at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:02.430 --> 00:42:07.260
the level of algorithms to check whether this&nbsp;
algorithm is the same as the zero algorithm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:07.260 --> 00:42:15.000
that just says print zero, no matter what. So&nbsp;
this is a very key problem that means that you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:23.730
can't have a surefire way of checking whether&nbsp;
two algorithms generate the same decimal number.

00:42:23.730 --> 00:42:31.290
So these next two difficulties are related.&nbsp;
The first is that it is difficult to find&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:31.290 --> 00:42:38.310
a canonical algorithm for an infinite decimal.&nbsp;
When it comes to rational numbers like this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:38.310 --> 00:42:46.770
we can reduce the denominator and the numerator&nbsp;
by any common factors so that we get to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:46.770 --> 00:42:52.740
situation where the numerator and denominator&nbsp;
do not have any common factors. And if we also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:59.760
agree that the denominator is always positive,&nbsp;
then we get a canonical or standard form for a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:59.760 --> 00:43:05.700
rational number. That means whenever we have an&nbsp;
arithmetic problem involving a rational number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:05.700 --> 00:43:12.360
we can ask for the answer in standard form,&nbsp;
which makes it very easy to check whether it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:19.740
the right answer or not. With real numbers, we&nbsp;
have no such situation. There are many different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:19.740 --> 00:43:25.620
algorithms for a given infinite decimal, and&nbsp;
there's no way of saying which one of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:31.860
algorithms is superior to the other ones. There's&nbsp;
no way of singling out a special algorithm that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:31.860 --> 00:43:39.300
we're going to be using exclusively for&nbsp;
that infinite decimal. So it becomes very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:39.300 --> 00:43:46.560
hard to tell when two infinite decimals are&nbsp;
equal, and so when I say "very hard," well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:51.000
it's pretty well impossible. So it's impossible&nbsp;
to tell when two infinite decimals are equal.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:44:00.050
Here's an example: This integral here with this&nbsp;
expression involving 22/7 in this integral,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:00.050 --> 00:44:07.280
that's a real number in the sense of&nbsp;
this integral being interpreted in some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:07.280 --> 00:44:11.900
fashion or another as an algorithm. In fact,&nbsp;
there are a whole bunch of algorithms that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:11.900 --> 00:44:17.420
one can use to sort of unravel what this&nbsp;
integral is, but you take one of those,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:17.420 --> 00:44:25.640
and you generate a real number. Here's another&nbsp;
algorithm in terms of an infinite series. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:25.640 --> 00:44:32.300
infinite series has some binomial coefficient&nbsp;
there, 2n choose n cubed, and then a fraction&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:39.980
42n plus 5 divided by 2 to the 12n plus 4—very&nbsp;
curious expression. Then we take the whole thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:39.980 --> 00:44:47.900
and take its inverse. This is a formula of the&nbsp;
great Indian mathematician Ramanujan. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:47.900 --> 00:44:54.200
a formula that appeared in the University of&nbsp;
Sydney exam in 1960. It turns out that they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:54.200 --> 00:45:01.730
both evaluate to pi. They are both expressions&nbsp;
for pi. There are among hundreds of expressions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:01.730 --> 00:45:07.820
that are known, but let's say you were just&nbsp;
given these two algorithms and asked, "Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:07.820 --> 00:45:16.580
are the decimals the same?" It would be very, very&nbsp;
hard to check that. Some very deep mathematical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:23.330
knowledge is necessary to recognize that both&nbsp;
of these happen to be expressions for pi.

00:45:23.330 --> 00:45:31.790
So one of the consequences of this is that&nbsp;
arithmetic with real numbers becomes vague and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:31.790 --> 00:45:39.710
often almost tautological. Students don't practice&nbsp;
doing arithmetic with real numbers because it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:39.710 --> 00:45:47.780
almost a non-existent subject except to the extent&nbsp;
that it contains rational numbers inside it. But,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:47.780 --> 00:45:51.980
for example, I've given you this problem in an&nbsp;
earlier video to calculate square root 2 plus pi&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:51.980 --> 00:45:58.910
plus e in the real number framework. So the modern&nbsp;
mathematician really has no answer to that other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:58.910 --> 00:46:04.070
than to say, "Well, the answer is square root 2&nbsp;
plus pi plus e." That's the simplest expression&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:13.400
that we have for this sum. Similarly, suppose you&nbsp;
just sort of write down a random infinite series,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:13.400 --> 00:46:18.980
summation n equals zero to infinity e&nbsp;
to the minus (n + 5) times n cubed over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:18.980 --> 00:46:25.940
n squared plus 1 factorial. Now, it might be&nbsp;
that this thing, you know, evaluates to some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:25.940 --> 00:46:33.890
rational number like 3/4—highly unlikely, but&nbsp;
it's possible. But in the absence of knowing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:33.890 --> 00:46:41.300
some particular special fact like that, we don't&nbsp;
know how to sum such series in general. And if a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:45.950
mathematician was asked to evaluate that, about&nbsp;
the only thing they could write down is this:

00:46:45.950 --> 00:46:50.330
"I’m going to solve this problem&nbsp;
for you. Here's how you do it:

00:46:50.330 --> 00:47:00.470
There, I've just solved it. I've&nbsp;
just evaluated that summation for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:00.470 --> 00:47:06.140
you. By the way, if anybody knows a&nbsp;
better answer, please let me know."

00:47:06.140 --> 00:47:14.000
Now, I'm going to evaluate this function.&nbsp;
So here's a numerical expression:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:18.290
I'm going to evaluate that here,&nbsp;
and this is the best I can do:

00:47:28.970 --> 00:47:31.790
Again, if you can do better&nbsp;
than that, please let us know.

00:47:31.790 --> 00:47:39.260
And now I'm going to evaluate this—this is an&nbsp;
integral. Alright, how do we evaluate that?

00:47:50.620 --> 00:47:58.090
Of course, I could write down an infinite decimal&nbsp;
approximation, okay, but that's only a rational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:58.090 --> 00:48:02.110
approximation. I can't actually write down that&nbsp;
infinite decimal. If I want to say exactly what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:02.110 --> 00:48:06.670
this is, really the only thing I can do is I can&nbsp;
repeat the question back to you as an answer.

00:48:06.670 --> 00:48:12.400
And finally, in the real number&nbsp;
framework, let's solve this problem:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:12.400 --> 00:48:19.060
1/2 plus 1/3 plus 1/5. Alright, if you're working&nbsp;
in the rational numbers, well then there's only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:19.060 --> 00:48:25.720
one possible answer, but if you're working&nbsp;
in the real numbers, algorithms are fluid,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:25.720 --> 00:48:31.870
and there's no special choice of algorithms.&nbsp;
So, in keeping with the things above here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:31.870 --> 00:48:37.420
I think a student is justified in writing,&nbsp;
"Well, there it is. There's the answer."

00:48:37.420 --> 00:48:42.640
Happy students doing arithmetic with real numbers!

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:50.140
So I'm being a bit facetious here, but this is&nbsp;
an issue. The issue is that we can't actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:56.560
effectively do arithmetic with real numbers at&nbsp;
all. And that's why first-year calculus books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:56.560 --> 00:49:01.870
after they introduce real numbers,&nbsp;
rarely ever have a section on "Now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:01.870 --> 00:49:05.920
let's practice a little bit of real&nbsp;
number arithmetic to get you used to it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:05.920 --> 00:49:10.090
to get you understanding how it&nbsp;
works." There's never a section&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:10.090 --> 00:49:16.990
like that because the arithmetic is vacuous&nbsp;
in some sense. It's a necessary consequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:22.600
of this imprecision that we get when we look&nbsp;
at things with an algorithmic point of view.

00:49:22.600 --> 00:49:28.960
Now, there are many other difficulties that&nbsp;
arise in mathematics as a consequence of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:28.960 --> 00:49:33.100
point of view towards real numbers, but&nbsp;
I'm going to stop here. These are sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:33.100 --> 00:49:40.750
of elementary considerations that are very&nbsp;
close to the core of the definition. So I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:40.750 --> 00:49:47.920
think the overall argument that I'm making here&nbsp;
is that trying to define real numbers in terms&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:47.920 --> 00:49:56.050
of algorithms doesn't work. It has not been&nbsp;
done; there are too many technical obstacles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:56.050 --> 00:50:02.020
and people are just playing some fantasy&nbsp;
game when they talk about this theory as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:02.020 --> 00:50:07.530
if the theory already exists. The theory is not&nbsp;
there, even though we would very much like it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:07.530 --> 00:50:12.810
to be there because that's what we use to do our&nbsp;
infinite series, to do our function evaluations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:12.810 --> 00:50:20.280
to do our integrals, and to do many other&nbsp;
things. So we see a serious disconnect in modern&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:20.280 --> 00:50:25.890
mathematics between rigorous thinking and the&nbsp;
actual practical application of what we're doing.

00:50:25.890 --> 00:50:35.940
Now, most pure mathematicians are going to be&nbsp;
reluctant to face the music here. The idea is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:35.940 --> 00:50:40.860
to avoid thinking about this problem because&nbsp;
most mathematicians are aware at some level&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:40.860 --> 00:50:47.640
that it's there. The agreement has been to "let's&nbsp;
not think about it too much," let's call all such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:51.900
discussion, "Oh, that's philosophy," or, "That&nbsp;
has to do with the foundations of mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:51.900 --> 00:50:56.820
which doesn't need to concern us." But it&nbsp;
ought to concern us very much because it has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:56.820 --> 00:51:03.120
very serious consequences for mathematics.&nbsp;
And once you start adopting lazy attitudes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:03.120 --> 00:51:08.610
towards rigor at this level, it starts&nbsp;
infiltrating other areas in mathematics.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:08.610 --> 00:51:13.440
Students learn that there are certain places&nbsp;
where it's allowed to be woefully vague, where&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:13.440 --> 00:51:22.830
it's allowed to be sort of hand-waving.&nbsp;
It's not an ideal situation, I think.

00:51:22.830 --> 00:51:28.740
Next time, what we're going to do is look&nbsp;
at a very important object historically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:28.740 --> 00:51:36.990
and one that many of you will probably like&nbsp;
very much: this magical object called pi. Is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:36.990 --> 00:51:42.420
it really a number? That is not so clear. I'm&nbsp;
going to introduce the idea that maybe pi is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:42.420 --> 00:51:48.390
something slightly different from a number in&nbsp;
the usual sense, so we'll have a historical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:48.390 --> 00:51:55.680
look at formulas for pi. I hope you'll join me for&nbsp;
that. I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

